cs.DS, cs.DB, cs.CG, cs.IR, cs.DC. 

This paper presents an external memory data structure for maintaining a dynamic set of points and supporting range reporting and top-$k$ queries. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the data structures (cs.DS), databases (cs.DB), computational geometry (cs.CG), information retrieval (cs.IR), or distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) sub-categories. However, since the focus of the paper is on data structures and algorithms, and the techniques used are primarily related to external memory, it is most likely to belong to the data structures (cs.DS) sub-category. The other sub-categories are also possible, but less likely.
